PROJECT 3: S3 Security Hardening
Date: Day 6
What I built:

Created S3 bucket with all security controls enabled from the start
Verified and enforced Block Public Access on all 4 settings
Applied bucket policy to deny all non-SSL (HTTP) requests — HTTPS only
Enabled Server Side Encryption using SSE-S3 on all objects
Created separate logging bucket and enabled Server Access Logging
Enabled and tested Bucket Versioning with multiple file versions
Configured Lifecycle Policy for automatic object expiry and cleanup
Conducted full S3 security audit against best practices

Security controls applied:

Block Public Access (all 4 settings ON)
Bucket Policy enforcing HTTPS only traffic
SSE-S3 encryption on all stored objects
ACLs disabled (recommended security setting)
Server Access Logging to dedicated log bucket
Bucket Versioning for data recovery and protection
Lifecycle Policy for automated cleanup and cost management
Object level encryption verified after upload

Security audit results:

Block Public Access: ON
Bucket Versioning: Enabled
Default Encryption SSE-S3: Enabled
Access Logging: Enabled
Bucket Policy HTTPS only: Applied
Public Object URL access: Access Denied
ACLs: Disabled
MFA Delete: Best practice noted (requires CLI)
Lifecycle Policy: Configured

Challenges faced and resolved:

Bucket policy returned Invalid Resource error
Diagnosed bucket name mismatch in ARN resource field
Fixed by correcting bucket name from dipes to dipesh
Policy saved successfully after correction
Lifecycle transition cost warning appeared
Resolved by removing transition actions to avoid charges
Kept expiry and cleanup rules only
Documented production vs lab environment difference

Real world value:

S3 misconfiguration is the number one cause of cloud data breaches globally
This exact hardening checklist is used by cloud security teams in every company
Demonstrates ability to secure, audit and maintain S3 buckets to production standard
Shows cost awareness by making smart decisions around lifecycle transitions

Key learnings:

Every character matters in AWS resource names and ARNs
Block Public Access alone is not enough — bucket policy adds extra layer
HTTPS enforcement prevents man in the middle attacks on data in transit
SSE-S3 protects data at rest from unauthorized access
Versioning protects against accidental deletion and ransomware
Access logging is essential for security audit trails
Lifecycle policies automate cleanup and prevent cost surprises
Always test security controls after applying them
